<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Why does text need to be escaped?", answer: "Text needs escaping when it crosses context boundaries. A double quote inside a JSON string would end the string prematurely. An ampersand in HTML would start an entity reference. A question mark in a URL would start the query string. Escaping replaces these special characters with safe sequences so that the text is interpreted as data, not as control characters in the target format." },
  { question: "What is the difference between URL encoding and HTML escaping?", answer: "URL encoding (percent-encoding) replaces reserved URL characters with percent sign followed by hex digits, such as %20 for space and %26 for ampersand. HTML escaping replaces characters that have special meaning in HTML with named or numeric entity references, such as &amp; for ampersand and &lt; for less-than. Each operates in its own context and the escape sequences are not interchangeable." },
  { question: "What is double escaping and how do I fix it?", answer: "Double escaping happens when text is escaped twice, producing sequences like &amp;amp; instead of &amp; or %2520 instead of %20. This occurs when code escapes text that was already escaped. To fix it, unescape the text completely, then re-escape it exactly once at the correct boundary. The key principle is to escape at the point of output, not at the point of input." },
  { question: "How do escaping failures cause security vulnerabilities?", answer: "Failing to escape user input leads to injection attacks. Unescaped HTML allows cross-site scripting (XSS) where attackers inject malicious scripts. Unescaped SQL allows SQL injection where attackers modify database queries. Unescaped shell arguments allow command injection. The defense is to always escape output for its target context using the language's built-in escaping functions." },
  { question: "What are Unicode escape sequences?", answer: "Unicode escape sequences represent characters using their Unicode code point in the format \\uXXXX where XXXX is the hexadecimal code point. For example, \\u00E9 represents the character e with acute accent. They are used in programming languages and data formats to include non-ASCII characters in ASCII-only contexts, ensuring compatibility across systems with different character encodings." }
]) %>

